{"cursor":"42675","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn physics, a 'frame of reference' (or 'reference frame') may refer to a\ncoordinate system used to represent and measure properties of objects such as\ntheir position and orientation. It may also refer to a set of axes used for such\nrepresentation.\n\nAlternatively, in relativity, the phrase can be used to refer to the\nrelationship between a moving observer and the phenomenon or phenomena under\nobservation. In this context, the phrase often becomes \"'observational frame of\nreference'\" (or \"'observational reference frame'\"). The context may itself\ninclude a coordinate system used to represent the observer and phenomenon or\nphenomena.\n","linknr":607,"url":"Frame_of_reference","recorded":1362484679,"links":58,"instances":["mechanical","linear_algebra","mathematics","geometry","physics","rotating_reference_frame","special_relativity"],"pdf":["http://www.pitt.edu/~jdnorton/papers/decades.pdf"],"categories":["Special relativity","Astronomy","Frames of reference|","Theory of relativity","Geodesy","Navigation","Surveying"],"headings":["Different aspects of \"frame of reference\"","Examples of inertial frames of reference","Non-inertial frames","Particular frames of reference in common use","See also","Notes","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/1/0/610bc52ec5a62efd154a01deb92a0d5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Referance_frame_and_observer.